art of hearer and speaker, with only incidental reading of oral dialogs and drills. From Unit XIII on there is a reading section designated for each unit, correlated with the primarily spoken materials, but designed to promote facility in the orthography and distinctive patterns of the written language. . . The basic format is as follows:A. Basic DialogB. Cultural and Structural NotesC. Pronunciation Exercises (to Unit XIII)D. Drills and GrammarE. Cumulative DrillsF. Visual-Cue DrillsG. Comprehension-Response DrillsH. Readings (from Unit XIII)"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aTagalog languagexGrammar. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBowen, J. Donald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520342897?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520342897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520342897/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles